with the Christian right and the
Republican Party, and also for

01:59.166 --> 02:02.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conservative South Carolina
Senator Strom Thurmond.

02:02.933 --> 02:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What was your own attitude
about poor black people and
black people in general?

02:07.600 --> 02:09.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN WILSON-HARTGROVE,
Co-Author, "The Third
Reconstruction: How
a Moral Movement

02:09.733 --> 02:10.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is Overcoming the Politics of
Division and Fear": So, I was
raised in the Southern Baptist

02:10.666 --> 02:12.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Church in a sundown town.

02:12.733 --> 02:15.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Until 1983, there was a sign
at the edge of our town that
told black people they weren't

02:15.766 --> 02:17.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
welcome there after
the sun went down.

02:17.800 --> 02:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: I have
read that you called yourself
a racist in those days.

02:20.166 --> 02:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JONATHAN WILSON-HARTGROVE: Sure.

02:22.266 --> 02:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I didn't know I was a racist,
but Reverend Barber helped me
see that I was racist, and,

02:25.533 --> 02:30.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more importantly, that my
racism was getting in the way
of loving Jesus, which is what

02:30.433 --> 02:32.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I really wanted to do.

02:32.500 --> 02:35.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT:
Wilson-Hartgrove first
heard Reverend Barber
some 20 years ago at

02:35.466 --> 02:38.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a meeting called by the
North Carolina governor.

02:38.566 --> 02:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Reverend Barber delivered
a motivational speech to a
gathering of young people.

02:43.400 --> 02:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wilson-Hartgrove was moved
by what Barber said and began
to understand how racism had

02:49.300 --> 02:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
been used as a tool to divide.

02:51.733 --> 02:56.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Growing up poor,
Wilson-Hartgrove had
never before realized
what he had in common with

02:56.266 --> 02:58.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
poor black people.

02:58.333 --> 03:01.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JONATHAN WILSON-HARTGROVE: We
were taught to believe that
there were people who were

03:01.500 --> 03:04.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
poor because they
chose to be poor.

03:04.233 --> 03:09.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that narrative kept us
from seeing the way that our
religion was being used to pit

03:10.100 --> 03:12.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
us against other people.

03:12.066 --> 03:15.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Reverend
Barber has even taken his
message into Appalachia, and

03:15.733 --> 03:17.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
up to Mitchell County,
North Carolina.

03:17.433 --> 03:19.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REV.

03:19.500 --> 03:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BARBER II: Mitchell
County, North Carolina is a
place where, in 1920, all the

03:22.533 --> 03:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
black people were run out of
town over the accusation of a
black man raping a white woman.

03:28.733 --> 03:32.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
